iugena (9. Jh.) Vater dieses cusanischen Konzeptes war.  aNicolas of Cusa’s notion of God as “non aliud” is one of the most spectacular ideas in the history of metaphysics – the negative self-reference of the Absolute. In this study, Max Rohstock examines this concept historically and systematically. For the first time, he shows Johannes Scotus Eriugena was the true progenitor of the concept.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAbsolute, The. 0aNegative theologyxChristianity. 0aNegative theology. 0aNeoplatonism. 0aOntologyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, MedievalxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aSelfxHistory. 4aJohannes Scottus Eriugena. 4aNegative Theologie. 4aNeuplatonismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh  aJohannes Scottus Eriugena.  aNegative theology.  aNeo-Platonism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Philosophy 2000 - 2014z9783110636949oZDB-23-GPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE DES MITTELALTERS ONLINEz9783110514827oZDB-23-PHM08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831103867690 cprintz978311035920640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311035924440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110359244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110359244/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-DPHb2014  aZDB-23-GPHc2000d2014  aZDB-23-PHM